Rule.Name: Abstract types should not have public constructors
Rule.Description: Public constructors for abstract types do not make sense because you cannot create instances of abstract types.

Rule.Name: Assemblies are marked CLSCompliant
Rule.Description: Assemblies should explicitly state their CLS compliance using the CLSCompliant attribute. An assembly without this attribute is not CLS-compliant.
Rule.LongDescription: Assemblies, modules, and types can be CLS-compliant even if some parts of the assembly, module, or type are not CLS-compliant. The following rules apply: 1) If the element is marked CLSCompliant, any noncompliant members must have the CLSCompliant attribute present with its argument set to false. 2) A comparable CLS-compliant alternative member must be supplied for each member that is not CLS-compliant.

Rule.Name: Assemblies specify permission requests
Rule.Description: Permission requests prevent security exceptions from being thrown after code in an assembly has already begun executing. With permission requests, the assembly does not load if it has insufficient permissions. This rule will generate a message if you have specified a permission request incorrectly, or incompletely. If you have specified requests but FxCop reports a message from this rule, use the PermView.exe tool to view the security permissions in the assembly. An unenforceable permission appears as an empty permission set.
Rule.LongDescription: You should add attributes specifying what permissions your assembly will demand, might demand, and what permissions it does not want granted. For example, the following attribute indicates that an assembly will, at minimum, require read access to the USERNAME environment variable: [assembly:EnvironmentPermissionAttribute(SecurityAction.RequestMinimum, Read="USERNAME")]. To specify permissions that the assembly might demand, use SecurityAction.RequestOptional. To specify permissions that the assembly must not be granted, use SecurityAction.RequestRefuse.

Rule.Name: Assemblies have strong names
Rule.Description: Assemblies with strong names can be placed in the global assembly cache and can be checked for tampering at run time.
Rule.LongDescription: The common language runtime compares the key in the assembly's manifest to the key used to generate the strong name, to ensure that the assembly's bits have not been tampered with.

Rule.Name: Assemblies have version numbers
Rule.Description: Assemblies should use version numbers. The version number is considered part of an assembly's identity.
Rule.LongDescription: Versioning is applied by means of the AssemblyVersion attribute.

Rule.Name: Assemblies should have the ComVisible attribute
Rule.Description: The ComVisible attribute indicates whether COM clients can use the library. Good design dictates that assemblies explicitly indicate COM visibility.
Rule.LongDescription: The default value for this attribute is 'true'. If the assembly will not be COM visible, mark it with [assembly:ComVisible(false)]. Types, interfaces, and individual members can also be marked with the ComVisible attribute. For more information, see the Design Guidelines section titled Exposing Functionality to COM.

Rule.Name: Avoid building non-callable code into assemblies
Rule.Description: There is code that appears to not be callable from a public or protected code path.
Rule.LongDescription: If this rule generates a message in error, please send a problem report to the FxCop team.

Rule.Name: Avoid building uninstantiated internal classes into assemblies
Rule.Description: An internal class was detected that is apparently never instantiated.
Rule.LongDescription: This rule does not attempt to detect late-bound creation and will generate false positives if instances of a type are only created in this way (for example, by means of Activator.CreateInstance or by passing the type as an argument to a TypeConverter constructor).

Rule.Name: Avoid having a namespace with a small number of types
Rule.Description: A namespace should generally have more than five types.

Rule.Name: Avoid creating static fields that are not constants
Rule.Description: Static fields should be constant unless you carefully manage access to the field using locks.
Rule.LongDescription: Using static variables without making them thread safe can compromise execution state. This rule applies to managed code libraries. If the analyzed assembly is an application, it is usually safe to exclude messages from this rule.

Rule.Name: Collection names have the 'Collection' suffix
Rule.Description: A type that implements ICollection or IEnumerable should be suffixed with 'Collection', as in StringCollection.
Rule.LongDescription: If a collection is a queue, it may also be suffixed with 'Queue', or if it is a stack, it may also be suffixed with 'Stack'. This is because these collections have semantic differences in use from other collections.

Rule.Name: Consider replacing methods with properties
Rule.Description: Properties should be used instead of Get/Set methods in most situations.
Rule.LongDescription: Methods are preferable to properties in the following situations: the operation is a conversion, is expensive or has an observable side-effect; the order of execution is important; calling the member twice in succession creates different results; a member is static but returns a mutable value; or the member returns an array.

Rule.Name: Delegate names do not have a 'Delegate' suffix
Rule.Description: Do not use 'Delegate' as a suffix on a Delegate type's name.
Rule.LongDescription: Consider using Callback instead.

Rule.Name: System.Exception and System.SystemException are not caught
Rule.Description: You should not catch Exception or SystemException.
Rule.LongDescription: Catching generic exception types can hide run-time problems from the library user, and can complicate debugging. You should catch only those exceptions that you can handle gracefully.

Rule.Name: Exceptions are marked Serializable
Rule.Description: In order to work properly in all scenarios, exceptions must be serializable and have the Serializable attribute.
Rule.LongDescription: For example, remoting requires that exceptions be serializable.

Rule.Name: Exceptions require multiple constructors
Rule.Description: Multiple constructors are required to correctly implement a custom exception.
Rule.LongDescription: Missing constructors can make your exception unusable in certain scenarios. For example, the serialization constructor is required for handling exceptions in XML Web services.

Rule.Name: Explicit method implementations in unsealed classes should provide alternate methods with protected accessibility
Rule.Description: Explicit method implementations are defined with private accessibility. Classes that derive from classes with explicit method implementations and choose to re-declare them on the class will not be able to call into the base class implementation unless the base class has provided an alternate method with appropriate accessibility.
Rule.LongDescription: When overriding a base class method that has been hidden by explicit interface implementation, in order to call into the base class implementation, a derived class must cast the base pointer to the relevant interface. When calling through this reference, however, the derived class implementation will actually be invoked, resulting in recursion and an eventual stack overflow.

Rule.Name: Externally visible nested types should not be used
Rule.Description: Do not use public, protected or protected internal (Protected Friend) nested types as a way of grouping types. Use namespaces for this purpose.
Rule.LongDescription: There are very limited scenarios where nested types are the best design. Also, nested type member accessibility is not clearly understood by all audiences. Enumerators are exempt from this rule.

Rule.Name: ICollection implementations have strongly typed members
Rule.Description: Types that implement ICollection should also provide a version of CopyTo with the first parameter set to a strong type, namely a type other than an array of objects or System.Array. Implement the interface member explicitly and make the strongly typed version public.
Rule.LongDescription: It is safe to ignore messages from this rule when you are implementing a new object-based collection, such as a binary tree, where types based on your collection will determine what the strong type is. These types should expose strongly typed members.

Rule.Name: IComparable implementations override operators
Rule.Description: Types that implement IComparable should redefine comparison operators to keep the meanings of less than, greater than, and equals consistent throughout the type.

Rule.Name: IFormatProvider should be passed
Rule.Description: If an overload exists that takes an IFormatProvider argument, it should always be called in favor of an overload that does not.
Rule.LongDescription: Some methods in the common language runtime convert a value to or from a string representation and take a string parameter that contains one or more characters, called format specifiers, which indicate how the value is to be converted. If the meaning of the format specifier varies by culture, a formatting object supplies the actual characters used in the string representation. In scenarios where sorting and comparison behavior should never change between cultures, specify CultureInfo.InvariantCulture.

Rule.Name: IList implementations have strongly typed members
Rule.Description: IList implementations should also provide versions of the IList members that are strongly typed, namely they should specify types other than Object for method and property parameter and return types. Implement the interface members explicitly and make the strongly typed versions public.
Rule.LongDescription: It is safe to ignore messages from this rule when you are implementing a new object-based collection, such as a linked list, where types based on your collection will determine what the strong type is. These types should expose strongly typed members.

Rule.Name: Interface definitions should not be empty
Rule.Description: Interfaces are meant to contain members that specify a set of behaviors. To mark or label a class, use an attribute instead of an empty interface.

Rule.Name: Member names are Pascal-cased
Rule.Description: Use Pascal casing for all class, namespace, and member identifiers.
Rule.LongDescription: This convention capitalizes the first letter of each word, as in BackColor. Use Pascal casing for all public identifiers consisting of compound words.

Rule.Name: Member names do not contain underscores
Rule.Description: Do not use underscores when specifying member names.
Rule.LongDescription: Some generated Visual Studio identifiers for applications contain underscore characters. Underscore characters should generally be avoided in public identifiers.

Rule.Name: Member name acronyms of three or more characters are Pascal-cased
Rule.Description: Acronyms of three or more letters should be Pascal-cased. For example, use XmlSpace rather than XMLSpace.
Rule.LongDescription: A violation of this rule might be required for compatibility with existing, non-managed symbol schemes. In general, however, these symbols should not be visible outside the assembly that uses them.

Rule.Name: Member name acronyms with two characters are all capitals
Rule.Description: Two character acronyms should be in upper-case. For example, use System.IO instead of System.Io.
Rule.LongDescription: Although it may be common practice for some two character acronyms to not be fully capitalized, messages from this rule should not be excluded for this reason. For example, 'DbConnection', is common but incorrect; use DBConnection. A violation of this rule might be required for compatibility with existing, non-managed symbol schemes. In general, however, these symbols should not be visible outside the assembly that uses them.

Rule.Name: Member names should consist of correctly spelled words
Rule.Description: The individual words that make up a member name should not be abbreviated and should be spelled correctly.
Rule.LongDescription: If this rule generates a false positive on a term that should be recognized, add the word to the FxCop custom dictionary.

Rule.Name: Namespace names are Pascal-cased
Rule.Description: Use Pascal casing for all type, namespace, and member identifiers.
Rule.LongDescription: This convention capitalizes the first character of each word, as in System.EnterpriseServices. Use Pascal casing for all public identifiers consisting of compound words.

Rule.Name: Namespace names should consist of correctly spelled words
Rule.Description: The individual words that make up a namespace should not be abbreviated and should be spelled correctly.
Rule.LongDescription: If this rule generates a false positive on a term that should be recognized, add the word to the FxCop custom dictionary.

Rule.Name: Only event handler names have the 'EventHandler' suffix
Rule.Description: The name of a type that is not an event handler should not be suffixed with 'EventHandler'.

Rule.Name: Parameter names do not match reserved keywords
Rule.Description: Identifiers which match reserved keywords should be avoided. Matching is performed case-insensitively.
Rule.LongDescription: Names that describe the purpose or contents of a parameter are preferable to names that describe the data type or format. If a parameter has no descriptive information other than its type, use a generic name such as 'value'.

Rule.Name: Parameter names do not match member names
Rule.Description: Parameter names should be distinct from member names.

Rule.Name: Parameter names should consist of correctly spelled words
Rule.Description: The individual words that make up a parameter name should not be abbreviated and should be spelled correctly.
Rule.LongDescription: If this rule generates a false positive on a term that should be recognized, add the word to the FxCop custom dictionary.

Rule.Name: Parameter names should use complete words
Rule.Description: Avoid parameter names that are cryptic or that use Hungarian notation.
Rule.LongDescription: Use complete words and avoid type prefixes such as ptr.

Rule.Name: Parameter names should not contain type names
Rule.Description: Do not use type names to name parameters; use a generic name instead.
Rule.LongDescription: Types names might not be intuitive for all developers. It is recommended that you select a generic name. If this is not sufficient, be sure to use the type name as it is defined in the .NET Framework Library. For example, use 'Boolean' instead of 'Bool'.

Rule.Name: Properties that return collections should be read-only
Rule.Description: Properties that return collections should be read-only so that users cannot entirely replace the backing store. Users can still modify the contents of the collection by calling relevant methods on the collection.
Rule.LongDescription: Note that the XmlSerializer class has special support for deserializing read-only collections. See the XmlSerializer overview for more information.

Rule.Name: Properties should not be write-only
Rule.Description: Write-only properties usually indicate a flawed design.

Rule.Name: Properties should not return arrays
Rule.Description: Properties that return arrays are prone to code inefficiencies.
Rule.LongDescription: Consider using a collection or making this a method. See the design guidelines for more information.

Rule.Name: Types that implement ISerializable should implement a serialization (magic) constructor
Rule.Description: The constructor signature accepts the same arguments as ISerializable.GetObjectData, namely, a SerializationInfo instance and a StreamingContext instance. The constructor should be protected for non-sealed classes and private for sealed classes.
Rule.LongDescription: Failure to implement a serialization constructor will cause deserialization to fail, and throw a SerializationException.

Rule.Name: Test for empty strings using System.String.Length
Rule.Description: To test for empty strings, check if String.Length is equal to zero.
Rule.LongDescription: Constructs such as "".Equals(someString) and String.Empty.Equals(someString) are less efficient than testing the string length. Replace these with checks for someString.Length == 0.

Rule.Name: Type names should consist of correctly spelled words
Rule.Description: The individual words that make up a type name should not be abbreviated and should be spelled correctly.
Rule.LongDescription: If this rule generates a false positive on a term that should be recognized, add the word to the FxCop custom dictionary.

Rule.Name: Types that allocate unmanaged resources implement IDisposable
Rule.Description: Types that allocate unmanaged resources should implement IDisposable to allow callers to release those resources on demand.
Rule.LongDescription: Failure to implement IDisposable can result in unmanaged resources being unavailable or underutilized.

Rule.Name: Types do not have externally visible instance fields
Rule.Description: Public or protected instance fields limit your ability to change the implementation details for those data items.
Rule.LongDescription: Use properties instead. They do not compromise usability or performance and they do provide flexibility in that they conceal the implementation details of the underlying data.

Rule.Name: Types with only static members should be sealed (NotInheritable)
Rule.Description: Static holder types do not provide functionality that derived instances can extend. Inheriting from such a type indicates a flawed design.

Rule.Name: Types with only static members should not have public or protected constructors
Rule.Description: Instances of types that define only static members do not need to be created.
Rule.LongDescription: Many compilers will automatically add a public default constructor if no constructor is specified. To prevent this, adding an empty private constructor may be required.
